*Rectangle.IsEmpty* and *Rectangle.Empty* should be corrected, as using either of these could lead to bugs via false negatives.

The current implementation is:
```
/// <summary>
/// Whether or not this <see cref="Rectangle"/> has a <see cref="Width"/> and
/// <see cref="Height"/> of 0, and a <see cref="Location"/> of (0, 0).
/// </summary>
public bool IsEmpty
{
    get
    {
        return ((((this.Width == 0) && (this.Height == 0)) && (this.X == 0)) && (this.Y == 0));
    }
}
```
According to this, for a *Rectangle* to be considered empty, both it's width *and* its height **must** equal 0 **and** both its X and Y positions **must** equal 0.

For a Rectangle to actually be empty, all that is required is that *either* its width **or** height equal 0. Its X or Y positions have no effect on this. A rectangle could have a height of *int.MaxValue* but if its width is 0, its still an empty triangle containing a no space. Essentially it would just be a line with no volume. It also doesn't matter if an empty Rectangle is located in the top-left of screen or the bottom-right; empty is still empty.

A correct implementation of *Rectangle.IsEmpty* would be:
```
public bool IsEmpty
{
    get { return Width == 0 || Height == 0; }
}
```
I realize this is legacy dragged along from XNA but regardless, its still incorrect and bugged against what should be expected behavior.

This also applies to the *Rectangle.Empty* constant which really shouldn't be labeled the definitive state of an empty Rectangle. As mentioned above, the X and Y positions have no context in whether it is empty and only a width **or** height of 0 indicate emptiness. Removing or renaming the *Rectangle.Empty* constant could be a breaking change to anyone compiled against it to determine emptiness in their code which sucks but if they're depending on this being the only form of an empty rectangle possible than their code is already bugged.

Any chance on a pull request to correct this or any thoughts against a PR for this?

Hi there, I'm having some trouble using `Effect` on some Android devices.  
I'll try to be understandable (feel free to ask stuff if I'm not).  

My tests are performed on two devices: Samsung Galaxy S4 (Android 5.0.1) and Samsung Galaxy Tab 2 (Android 6.0.1). I should note that I'm using other 6.0.1 devices without any issue.  
Galaxy S4 screenshots will be on the left and Galaxy Tab 2 on the right.

Everything is built through MonoGame Pipeline 3.5

---

**1rst test**: using a shader which outputs red pixels to draw on screen
```glsl
#if OPENGL
#define PS_SHADERMODEL ps_3_0
#else
#define PS_SHADERMODEL ps_4_0_level_9_1
#endif

float4 PixelShaderFunction(float2 pos : SV_POSITION, float4 color1 : COLOR0, float2 coords : TEXCOORD0) : COLOR0
{
	return float4(1, 0, 0, 1);
}

technique Technique1
{
	pass Pass1
	{
		PixelShader = compile PS_SHADERMODEL PixelShaderFunction();
	}
};
```

```cs
// ...
this.shader = this.Manager.Game.Content.Load<Effect>("shaders/credits");
// ...
this.spriteBatch.Begin(SpriteSortMode.Immediate, BlendState.AlphaBlend, null, null, null, this.shader);
this.spriteBatch.Draw(this.credits, this.creditsViewport, this.creditsSource, Color.White);
this.spriteBatch.End();
// ...
```
Everything is fine on both devices.
![screenshot_2017-07-21-15-05-18](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/437025/28464951-73389540-6e27-11e7-9b0f-199bce5614bc.png)

---

**2nd test**: using a shader which outputs texture as-is to draw on screen (C# code is same as above)
```glsl
#if OPENGL
#define PS_SHADERMODEL ps_3_0
#else
#define PS_SHADERMODEL ps_4_0_level_9_1
#endif

sampler ColorSampler : register(s0);

float4 PixelShaderFunction(float2 pos : SV_POSITION, float4 color1 : COLOR0, float2 coords : TEXCOORD0) : COLOR0
{
	return tex2D(ColorSampler, coords);
}

technique Technique1
{
	pass Pass1
	{
		PixelShader = compile PS_SHADERMODEL PixelShaderFunction();
	}
};
```
Everything is fine on the Galaxy S4 but nothing is drawn on the Galaxy Tab 2.
![screen](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/437025/28466074-6cf75be0-6e2b-11e7-83ba-5a643fdb6cf7.png)

---

**3rd test**: using the same shader as **2nd test** but on another `RenderTarget2D`
```cs
//...
Effect shader = this.Manager.Game.Content.Load<Effect>("shaders/credits");
SpriteBatch spriteBatch = new SpriteBatch(this.Manager.GraphicsDevice);

this.fade = new RenderTarget2D(this.Manager.GraphicsDevice, this.Manager.GraphicsDevice.Viewport.Width, this.Manager.GraphicsDevice.Viewport.Height);

this.Manager.Game.GraphicsDevice.SetRenderTarget(this.fade as RenderTarget2D);
this.Manager.Game.GraphicsDevice.Clear(Color.Transparent);
spriteBatch.Begin(SpriteSortMode.Deferred, BlendState.AlphaBlend, null, null, null, shader);
spriteBatch.Draw(this.background[0].Texture, this.fade.Bounds, Color.White);
spriteBatch.End();
this.Manager.Game.GraphicsDevice.SetRenderTargets();
//...
```
From now on (and no matter if I do something with `this.fade` or not), here's what kind of stuff is drawn on the Galaxy Tab 2 screen (no issue on the other device).

![screenshot_20170721-154119](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/437025/28466123-96079a4a-6e2b-11e7-9000-409b828bf22a.png)

And then, every single thing I draw on screen is broken (left picture is for comparison).
![screen](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/437025/28466239-16f81eae-6e2c-11e7-966e-eae8e5cb4441.png)



---

I am not that experienced with shaders so... Am I doing everything wrong? Is this somehow understandable?  
Thanks!

